snippet.textDisplay:
I find it curious that the "Huawei spying" idea has almost exclusively spun from Americanized rhetoric, not hard evidence. But then again, that seems to have become the going trend the last 5'ish years when just about _any_ two competing entities find themselves in a situation where one of them wants to win at any cost but can't really beat the competition on actual merits.

I have no doubt the Chinese government do their spying, as most nations do. But given the _known, documented track record,_ IMO the _last_ entities anyone should trust when it comes to any sort of ongoing or potential covert or illegal surveillance - or their public word and declarations - is the US government. And from what we know about their strong-arming and ethics history with forcing backdoors on companies, or if that fails, hacking - that by extent sadly goes for US-based _commercial_ entities too.
